---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout>
    <main class="p-8 max-w-4xl mx-auto text-aura-black bg-aura-soft rounded-2xl shadow">
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-aura-deep mb-4">What is an AURA Block?</h1>

        <section class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-justify text-aura-black mb-6">
            <p>
                An <strong>AURA block</strong> is a structured metadata file used to document and trace the use of
                generative AI systems (like GPT, DALL·E, Stable Diffusion) in content creation. Its purpose is to
                provide transparency, attribution, and reproducibility for AI-assisted outputs.
            </p>
            <p>
                Each AURA block is saved as a <code>.aura</code> file, which is internally a JSON structure with a
                specific schema. These files can be shared, inspected, validated, or archived.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-8">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-aura-leather mb-4">Typical Fields in a Block</h2>
            <div class="overflow-x-auto text-sm">
                <table class="min-w-full table-auto border-collapse border border-gray-300">
                    <thead class="bg-aura-cream">
                    <tr>
                        <th class="border px-4 py-2 text-left">Field</th>
                        <th class="border px-4 py-2 text-left">Description</th>
                    </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                    <tr><td class="border px-4 py-2 font-mono">uid</td><td class="border px-4 py-2">Unique identifier (e.g., AURA-2025-000001)</td></tr>
                    <tr><td class="border px-4 py-2 font-mono">model</td><td class="border px-4 py-2">The generative model used (e.g., GPT-4o, Stable Diffusion)</td></tr>
                    <tr><td class="border px-4 py-2 font-mono">prompt</td><td class="border px-4 py-2">The input or query that triggered the generation</td></tr>
                    <tr><td class="border px-4 py-2 font-mono">timestamp</td><td class="border px-4 py-2">ISO timestamp when the block was created</td></tr>
                    <tr><td class="border px-4 py-2 font-mono">provider</td><td class="border px-4 py-2">The platform or API that hosted the model</td></tr>
                    <tr><td class="border px-4 py-2 font-mono">content_hash</td><td class="border px-4 py-2">SHA-256 or similar hash for verifying the output’s integrity</td></tr>
                    <tr><td class="border px-4 py-2 font-mono">user_edit</td><td class="border px-4 py-2">Whether the content was edited after generation</td></tr>
                    <tr><td class="border px-4 py-2 font-mono">notes</td><td class="border px-4 py-2">Optional user notes or context</td></tr>
                    <tr><td class="border px-4 py-2 font-mono">license</td><td class="border px-4 py-2">Declared usage license (e.g., CC-BY-4.0)</td></tr>
                    <tr><td class="border px-4 py-2 font-mono">aura_version</td><td class="border px-4 py-2">Version of the AURA protocol schema</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section class="prose prose-sm text-aura-gray">
            <p>
                You can download AURA blocks as <code>.aura</code> files and store them alongside generated content,
                or submit them to a public registry. These files are self-contained and interoperable with any system
                that supports JSON.
            </p>
        </section>
    </main>
</Layout>
